

List - homogeneous collection of data with positions
	Array based list
	- Fixed Size
	- A lot of Data moving when updating
	- Searching when unordered is slow (same for any unordered structure)
	- Any insertion or deletion is complicated
	+ Has Direct index access
	
	Dynamic Data Structures are the opposite of a Fixed Data Structure (ie Arrays)
		Pointers and Vectors
		
	NODE FOR A LINKED LIST / WHICH IS A DYNAMIC STRUCTURE
______BLANK NodeType______________________________
	/* Chance Womack
	 * Blank Node Type
	 */
	 
	// include desired libraries and define class

	#ifndef H_NODETYPE
	#define H_NODETYPE
	#include <iostream>
	#include <iomanip>

		template <typename T>
		class NodeType
		{ // start def
		public:
			T data; // variable declaration
			NodeType<T> *next; // variable declaration
			
			NodeType(T d=0) { data = d; next = nullptr; } // constructor
		}; // end def
	#endif
_______________________________________________



Building a Linked List

	1: Building Foward (insert new items at the end of the list)
	
	
Doubly Linked Lists
	Different Node Structure: 1 Data + Next Point + Previous Pointer
	
	Each Node points to both the next node and the previous node


Circular Linked List
	Last node points to the first node



		
